<img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Anyway, has anyone else checked out Jackson's other films? I first discovered him during the summer of '88 or '89 during my jr. high B-horror flick faze. I rented a particularly low-budget looking film called, &quot;Bad Taste.&quot; I'm not sure if it was his first film (it is to my knowledge), but it was quite possibly the most disgusting (gore-wise) film I'd seen at that point. Yeah, it was &quot;low-budget&quot; looking, but it still managed to be more repulsive than most &quot;big-budget&quot; Hollywood splatter films. Needless to say, I took note of the obscure New Zelander's name and made it a point to watch for what he did in the future. <br>
<br>
   Fast-forward to my sophomore year of college at the local cult-video store. I guess I've never shaken my adolescent love of ultra-violent B-horror movies, because I frequently find myself inexorably drawn to these films even today. While looking through the cult-movie section, I found &quot;Dead Alive.&quot; I read the box proclaiming it as the goriest film of all time. This I had to see. &quot;Goriest film of all time, bah. Let's see it outdo Peter Jackson's 'Bad Taste.'&quot; I thought. Out of curiousity, I look through the credits on the back to see who directed it and damn near orgasmed when I saw his name, Lol. This I had to see. Who could outdo the man who had raised the bar on gore, but the man himself. Needless to say, the box lived up to its hype, hehe. Both &quot;Dead Alive&quot; &amp; &quot;Bad Taste&quot; exhibit the gore that's fun to laugh at, as popularized by Raimi's &quot;Evil Dead&quot; trilogy. It was obvious that &quot;Bad Taste&quot; had raised enough eyebrows to warrant a greater budget for &quot;Dead Alive&quot; and it was only a matter of time before Hollywood came calling with check in hand.<br>
<br>
   The result of the inevitable Hollywood money was a typically mediocre horror/comedy starring, Michael J. Fox. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  The movie is, &quot;The Frighteners,&quot; and while entertaining, it lacked the soul of his other films. IMO, the movie's only saving grace was the casting of Sgt. Hartman from &quot;Full Metal Jacket&quot; as the ghost of (you guessed it) a drill sgt.<br>
<br>
   &quot;Meet The Feebles&quot; is Jackson's parody of The Muppet Show. Imagine all the muppet show characters with RL problems. The Feebles' variety show featured a promiscuous, potentially HIV positive rabbit, a former vietnam vet, junky frog, knife thrower, and an obese female hippo singer (among others, heh). This is the movie I felt Jackson's genius truly began to shine. The animals he chose to represent the various different elements in society were perfect. The roach S&amp;M master whipping the udderly voluptuous cow (the udders were pierced too, Lol).<br>
<br>
   I'll be honest, I have not seen &quot;Heavenly Creatures.&quot; Prior to LoTR, it was the only &quot;drama&quot; he'd done that I'm aware of. Not much to say here since I haven't seen it. I know that it's supposedly based on a true-story and the critics seemed to be quite impressed, but that's about it.<br>
<br>
   The last thing I've seen by him was, &quot;Forgotten Silver.&quot; It's a relatively short docu-spoof that supposedly proves that colorized filming was actually invented by a fictional New Zeland director. It's well done and pretty funny at parts, but like I said, it's short. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
   I'm happy that LoTR is being received so well because I feel it's about time Jackson was given the respect he deserves. I hope to see it for myself this weekend. So, if you enjoyed LoTR and you've never seen any of Jackson's other movies, I highly recommend heading to your nearest &quot;Mom &amp; Pop&quot; video store and renting these. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  BTW, DO NOT RENT ANY OF HIS FILMS FROM BLOCKBUSTER. Those bastards cut all the best parts of his movies /rude &quot;family values BS.&quot;<br>
